entries.utterer: This folder contains links to the different EPISODES Google Sheets, inside of each you will find TABS for the different SCENES. These spreadsheets are PROXIES that are downloaded into the game.

entries.context: Here's how the process is going to work:
Update the text in the specific language column (be careful not to delete something in another column!)
When you want to see your translations in action, please send a message in the Discord to request a Sync.
Patrick will sync the files and then let you know that the scenes have been updated. You can then play the scene inside of Unity to check line lengths.
The cells in each sheet are spaces to a specific width that roughly equals the amount of characters in the box. Please do not adjust them.
If your translated cell has more than 3 lines, tag Patrick or Milton in a comment or message in Discord for them to test if the text fits or if it needs to be trimmed down.

entries.utterer: IMPORTANT INFORMATION TO KEEP IN MIND WHEN WRITING

entries.context: The donkeys have genders. The core members are:
Herd (the Herd is the main characters' herd, not capitalized for other herds referenced in E7 or E10)
Soul (only when noun, not adjective, i.e. soulless)
Protest (when a noun, not verb, i.e. to protest)
Reassignment (only when noun, to verb, i.e. to reassgin)
If you find strange spaces and symbols in the original English, be sure to follow it exactly as they are for programming or spacing purposes.
In English, we use — (m-dash) not - (hyphen) or – (n-dash). We will discuss the appropriate version for each translation.

In the middle of a sentence, we use spaces after eplipses... And the next sentence/fragment.

...But an elipsis at the beginning of a sentence does not have a space.
For Slow Ass, we try to repeat the stutter letter 3 times. (eg. What's the p-p-problem)

entries.utterer: Exploring adding vowels and Limburger dialects for Slow
Poep – A soft, child-friendly term for butt.
Bips – Cute and widely used; similar to "bum."
Billen – Literally "buttocks," but often used casually.
Gat – Literally "hole," but colloquially refers to the butt.
Kont – Direct and common; akin to "ass."
Achterwerk – A more neutral term; literally "rear work."
Achterste – Literally "hindmost," used to denote the backside.
Reet – A bit more vulgar; akin to "arse."
Krent – Literally "currant," used humorously for a small butt.
Aars – Anatomical term, but can be used colloquially.
Derrière – Borrowed from French; sounds fancy.
Billen – Used in a gentle context.
Paleto – hick (more derogatory, used in Spain)
Ranchero – rancher or cowboy (used in Mexico)
Gañán – peasant or laborer (sometimes derogatory, used in Spain)
Montuno – hillbilly or mountain dweller (used in various regions)
Paisano – countryman (neutral or affectionate in Latin America)
Guajiro – rural person, especially in Cuba
Charro – cowboy (Mexico), also used to mean unsophisticated
Cholo – originally indigenous or mestizo rural worker (can be affectionate in parts of Latin America)
Jíbaro – rural person, especially in Puerto Rico
Chunche – country bumpkin or unsophisticated person (Central America)
Catracho – rural person (used in Honduras, though it generally refers to Hondurans)
Llanero – plainsman or rural person (Venezuela and Colombia)
Serrano – mountain person (Andean regions, neutral or affectionate)
Ranchuco – similar to "ranchero" but more colloquial (Mexico)
Cocoliche – person with mixed European rural customs (Argentina, sometimes humorous or affectionate)
Pompis – bum (mild and often used with kids)
Culo – butt (common but can be a bit vulgar)
Fundillo – rear end (often humorous or informal)
Cachetes – cheeks (used in Mexico and other regions)
Derrière – derived from French, sometimes fancy or playful
Bubis – bottom (also used for chest, context matters)
Pandero – behind (often used in Mexico, humorous)
Pompas – bum (mild and used with kids, especially in Mexico)
Traserón – big rear end (informal or humorous)
Cachas – cheeks (informal, used in Spain and Latin America)
Tambor – drum (suggests a rounded shape, humorous)
Chichis – bum (can also mean chest, regional)
Posaderas – formal way to say backside
Bishos – bum (regional slang, especially in Spain)
Caderotas – big hips or rear (informal and humorous)
Cajuelas – crates (regional, often in Central America)
Carguro – informal form of "to charge up"
Peruro – adjective form for something from Peru
Burro/a – slang for a foolish person
Recurrir – to recur, to resort to
Manioburro – person with poor manual skill (regional)
Feturo – colloquial form of "to let something go"
Emburo – regional word meaning to force
Curro – work or job (slang in Spain)
Gansada – foolish remark (commonly used in Spain and Latin America)
Babosada – foolishness (often in Mexico and Central America)
Sonsera – nonsense (commonly used in Argentina and Chile)
Pavada – nonsense or silly thing (used in Argentina and Uruguay)
Yacimiento – deposit (referring to mineral or coal deposits)
Antracita – anthracite (a type of hard coal)
Terril – slag heap or coal waste pile
Galería – gallery or tunnel in a mine
Burro – the standard word for donkey
Asno – ass or donkey (more formal or old-fashioned)
Pollino – donkey (common in Spain, more poetic)
Borrico – small donkey or colt (used in Spain, informal)
Mulo – mule (though technically different, sometimes used interchangeably)
Bestia – beast (colloquially used to refer to a donkey)
Macilento – bony or weak donkey (regional, used in Latin America)
Choncho – colloquial term for donkey (used in Mexico, informal)
